  <h2>The package</h2>

  <p>
    It provides reusable tools for finding, filtering, reusing, evaluating, and
    diagnosing analogs: states in a catalog that are close to a query state
    according to a chosen representation and distance.
  </p>

  <p>
    The package{' '}
    {/* TODO: replace with real documentation URL */}
    <a href="#todo-docs">documentation</a>{' '}
    provides information on the package&rsquo;s functionalities, installation
    and use, as well as dedicated and easy-to-follow tutorials for beginners.
  </p>

  <h2>Why pyanalogs?</h2>

  <p>
    Nearest-neighbor search can be done efficiently with existing libraries such
    as <code>scikit-learn</code>. However, analog methods usually need more than
    raw nearest-neighbor search.
  </p>

  <p>In practice, analog workflows often require:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>temporal exclusions, such as not using samples too close in time;</li>
    <li>seasonal windows, such as searching only around the same time of year;</li>
    <li>
      group exclusions, such as not using samples from the same cyclone, event,
      ensemble member, or simulation;
    </li>
    <li>
      geophysical data handling, including <code>xarray</code> and NetCDF
      datasets;
    </li>
    <li>
      reusable analog indices and distances, so that one expensive search can
      support several downstream analyses;
    </li>
    <li>ensemble-based prediction, not only point prediction;</li>
    <li>probabilistic scoring, such as CRPS;</li>
    <li>
      sensitivity studies over the number of analogs, distance choices, variable
      weights, catalog size, and eligibility rules, which can become tedious.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Although simple in theory, using analog methods actually requires careful
    implementation and good practice that this package aims to facilitate. The
    package also includes documentation and tutorials which allow the unfamiliar
    user to delve easily in the world of analog methods.
  </p>

  <p>
    Recent work also combines analog methods with more advanced AI tools: metric
    optimization, representation learning. These methods are more difficult to
    implement than basic analog search, especially for users who are not
    specialists in numerical optimization or machine learning.
  </p>

  <p>
    <code>pyanalogs</code> aims to provide a common, tested, and extensible
    framework where classical analog methods, diagnostic tools, and newer
    analog-AI hybrid methods can be implemented, compared, and used by a broad
    scientific community.
  </p>

